  "prompt": "How do I find the average acceleration?",
  "response": "To find the average acceleration, follow these steps:\n\n1) Calculate the change in velocity (\u0394v):\n   \u0394v = Final velocity - Initial velocity\n\n2) Calculate the change in time (\u0394t):\n   \u0394t = Final time - Initial time\n\n3) Use the average acceleration formula:\n   Average Acceleration = \u0394v \u00f7 \u0394t\n\nThe units will typically be meters per second squared (m/s\u00b2).\n\nExample:\n\u2022 Initial velocity = 0 m/s\n\u2022 Final velocity = 20 m/s\n\u2022 Time elapsed = 4 seconds\n\n\u0394v = 20 m/s - 0 m/s = 20 m/s\n\u0394t = 4 s\nAverage Acceleration = 20 m/s \u00f7 4 s = 5 m/s\u00b2\n\nRemember: Average acceleration represents the rate of change of velocity over a specific time interval.",
